## Model Output: Research Question 2

::: {.cell}
::: {.cell-output-display}
![A visualization of the model output meaning the slopes of each level of predictor variable as well their confidence interval. If a beta is given one or more *, such indicates that their respective p-value is statistically significant.](03-results_files/figure-pdf/fig-sjplot-1.pdf){#fig-sjplot}
:::
:::

$$
\begin{aligned}
\widehat{Total Space RatioPerPage} = -0.988 &+ 0.233\times French \\
&-0.058\times Other \\
&-0.015\times British \\
&-0.078\times German \\
&+ 0.571\times Spanish \\
&-0.011\times MoMA \\
&+ 0.023\times French \times MoMACountToYear\\
&+ 0.015 \times Other \times MoMACountToYear\\
&+ 0.014 \times British \times MoMACountToYear\\
&+ 0.022 \times German \times MoMACountToYear\\
&+ 0.032 \times Spanish \times MoMACountToYear\\
\end{aligned}
$$

After step-wise model evaluation, the model that is most parsimonious with an optimized AIC is a model using only artist nationality, the count to year of the number of exhibitions an artist is included in at the MoMA, and the interaction between the two.

::: {.cell}

:::

With a log transformation applied to the outcome variable as it is heavily right-skewed, my linear mixed-effects model yields a conditional r squared of 53.23%. Such denotes that 53.23% of the variance of total space ratio per page given to an artist in a given edition can be explained by the model.
